{"title_page": "Jai Shri Ram", "text_new": "{{Italics}} \n{{short description|Phrase meaning \"Hail Lord Rama\", often chanted in Hinduism}}\n[[File:Ram in Ayodhya.jpg|thumb|207x207px|A depiction of Ram in Ayodhya.]]\n'''''Jai Shri Ram''''' is a Hindi expression, translating to \"Glory to Lord [[Rama]]\" or \"Victory to Lord Rama\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-48882053 |title=The Hindu chant that became a murder cry |date=2019-07-10 |work=BBC News |access-date=2020-02-04 |language=en-GB}}</ref> The proclamation has been used as an informal greeting<ref>{{Cite book |last=Menon |first=Kalyani Devaki |url=https://www.degruyter.com/view/product/454038 |title=Everyday Nationalism: Women of the Hindu Right in India |date=2011-07-06 |publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press |isbn=978-0-8122-0279-3 |page=190 |language=en |chapter=Notes |doi=10.9783/9780812202793 |jstor=j.ctt3fj1wh |chapter-url=https://www.degruyter.com/view/books/9780812202793/9780812202793.183/9780812202793.183.xml}}</ref> or as a symbol of adhering to Hindu [[faith]]<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Agrawal |first=Purushottam |date=1994 |title='Kan Kan Mein Vyape Hein Ram': The Slogan as a Metaphor of Cultural Interrogation |journal=Oxford Literary Review |volume=16 |issue=1/2 |pages=245\u2013264 |doi=10.3366/olr.1994.010 |issn=0305-1498 |jstor=44244508}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Ghosh |first=Shohini |date=2000 |title=Hum Aapke Hain Koun...!: Pluralizing Pleasures of Viewership |journal=Social Scientist |volume=28 |issue=3/4 |pages=83\u201390 |doi=10.2307/3518192 |issn=0970-0293 |jstor=3518192}}</ref> or for projection of varied faith-centered emotions, by Hindus in recent past.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Ramachandran |first=Tanisha |date=2014-03-01 |title=A call to multiple arms! protesting the commoditization of hindu imagery in western society |journal=Material Religion |volume=10 |issue=1 |pages=54\u201375 |doi=10.2752/175183414X13909887177547 |issn=1743-2200}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |date=2019-08-20 |title=Modi's party will grow stronger in West Bengal |journal=Emerald Expert Briefings |language=en |doi=10.1108/OXAN-DB245910 |issn=2633-304X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Dasgupta |first=Amlan |date=2006 |editor-last=Bakhle |editor-first=Janaki |title=Rhythm and Rivalry |journal=Economic and Political Weekly |volume=41 |issue=36 |pages=3861\u20133863 |issn=0012-9976 |jstor=4418675}}</ref> \nThe expression was used by the [[Hindu nationalism|Hindu nationalist]] [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) which embraced the slogan in the late 20th century, as a tool of increasing the visibility of Hinduism in public spaces and went on to use it as a war-cry, for perpetration of communal atrocities against people of other faiths.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Jaffrelot |first=Christophe |author-link=Christophe Jaffrelot |date=July 2003 |title=Communal Riots in Gujarat: The State at Risk? |url=http://archiv.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/volltextserver/4127/1/hpsacp17.pdf |journal=Heidelberg Papers in South Asian and Comparative Politics |issue=17 |page=3 |doi=10.11588/heidok.00004127 |issn=1617-5069}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Engineer |first=Asghar Ali |date=1993 |title=Bastion of Communal Amity Crumbles |journal=Economic and Political Weekly |volume=28 |issue=7 |pages=262\u2013264 |issn=0012-9976 |jstor=4399390}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Breman |first=Jan |date=1993 |title=Anti-Muslim Pogrom in Surat |journal=Economic and Political Weekly |volume=28 |issue=16 |pages=737\u2013741 |issn=0012-9976 |jstor=4399608}}</ref>\n\n== Origins ==\nIn the  late 1980's, the slogan was popularised by [[Ramanand Sagar]]'s television series ''[[Ramayan (1987 TV series)|Ramayan]]'', where it was used by [[Hanuman]] and the monkey army as a war cry when they fought the demon army of [[Ravan]] in order to free [[Sita]].<ref name=\"India Today\" /> The [[Vishva Hindu Parishad]] and its [[Sangh Parivar]] allies, including the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]], used it in their Ayodhya [[Ayodhya dispute|Ram Janmabhoomi movement]].<ref name=\"India Today\">{{Cite news |author=Prabash K. Dutta |title=Jai Shri Ram: A slogan that changed political contours of India |newspaper=India Today |date=13 July 2019 |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/jai-shri-ram-a-slogan-that-changed-political-contours-of-india-1568051-2019-07-13}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Vishva Hindu Parishad]]\n[[Category:Sangh Parivar]]\n[[Category:Ayodhya dispute]]\n[[Category:Violence against Muslims]]\n", "text_old": "{{Italics}} \n{{short description|Phrase meaning \"Hail Lord Rama\", often chanted in Hinduism}}\n[[File:Ram in Ayodhya.jpg|thumb|207x207px|A depiction of Ram in Ayodhya.]]\n'''''Jai Shri Ram''''' is a Hindi expression, translating to \"Glory to Lord [[Rama]]\" or \"Victory to Lord Rama\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-48882053 |title=The Hindu chant that became a murder cry |date=2019-07-10 |work=BBC News |access-date=2020-02-04 |language=en-GB}}</ref> The proclamation has been used as an informal greeting<ref>{{Cite book |last=Menon |first=Kalyani Devaki |url=https://www.degruyter.com/view/product/454038 |title=Everyday Nationalism: Women of the Hindu Right in India |date=2011-07-06 |publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press |isbn=978-0-8122-0279-3 |page=190 |language=en |chapter=Notes |doi=10.9783/9780812202793 |jstor=j.ctt3fj1wh |chapter-url=https://www.degruyter.com/view/books/9780812202793/9780812202793.183/9780812202793.183.xml}}</ref> or as a symbol of adhering to Hindu [[faith]]<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Agrawal |first=Purushottam |date=1994 |title='Kan Kan Mein Vyape Hein Ram': The Slogan as a Metaphor of Cultural Interrogation |journal=Oxford Literary Review |volume=16 |issue=1/2 |pages=245\u2013264 |doi=10.3366/olr.1994.010 |issn=0305-1498 |jstor=44244508}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Ghosh |first=Shohini |date=2000 |title=Hum Aapke Hain Koun...!: Pluralizing Pleasures of Viewership |journal=Social Scientist |volume=28 |issue=3/4 |pages=83\u201390 |doi=10.2307/3518192 |issn=0970-0293 |jstor=3518192}}</ref> or for projection of varied faith-centered emotions, by Hindus in recent past.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Ramachandran |first=Tanisha |date=2014-03-01 |title=A call to multiple arms! protesting the commoditization of hindu imagery in western society |journal=Material Religion |volume=10 |issue=1 |pages=54\u201375 |doi=10.2752/175183414X13909887177547 |issn=1743-2200}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |date=2019-08-20 |title=Modi's party will grow stronger in West Bengal |journal=Emerald Expert Briefings |language=en |doi=10.1108/OXAN-DB245910 |issn=2633-304X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Dasgupta |first=Amlan |date=2006 |editor-last=Bakhle |editor-first=Janaki |title=Rhythm and Rivalry |journal=Economic and Political Weekly |volume=41 |issue=36 |pages=3861\u20133863 |issn=0012-9976 |jstor=4418675}}</ref> \nThe expression was used by the [[Hindu nationalism|Hindu nationalist]] [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) which embraced the slogan in the late 20th century, as a tool of increasing the visibility of Hinduism in public spaces and went on to use it as a war-cry, for perpetration of communal atrocities against people of other faiths.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Jaffrelot |first=Christophe |author-link=Christophe Jaffrelot |date=July 2003 |title=Communal Riots in Gujarat: The State at Risk? |url=http://archiv.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/volltextserver/4127/1/hpsacp17.pdf |journal=Heidelberg Papers in South Asian and Comparative Politics |issue=17 |page=3 |doi=10.11588/heidok.00004127 |issn=1617-5069}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Engineer |first=Asghar Ali |date=1993 |title=Bastion of Communal Amity Crumbles |journal=Economic and Political Weekly |volume=28 |issue=7 |pages=262\u2013264 |issn=0012-9976 |jstor=4399390}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Breman |first=Jan |date=1993 |title=Anti-Muslim Pogrom in Surat |journal=Economic and Political Weekly |volume=28 |issue=16 |pages=737\u2013741 |issn=0012-9976 |jstor=4399608}}</ref>\n\n== Origins ==\nIn the  late 1980's, the slogan was popularised by [[Ramanand Sagar]]'s television series ''[[Ramayan (1987 TV series)|Ramayan]]'', where it was used by [[Hanuman]] and the monkey army as a war cry when they fought the demon army of [[Ravan]] in order to free [[Sita]].<ref name=\"India Today\" /> The [[Vishva Hindu Parishad]] and its [[Sangh Parivar]] allies, including the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]], used it in their Ayodhya [[Ayodhya dispute|Ram Janmabhoomi movement]].<ref name=\"India Today\">{{Cite news |author=Prabash K. Dutta |title=Jai Shri Ram: A slogan that changed political contours of India |newspaper=India Today |date=13 July 2019 |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/jai-shri-ram-a-slogan-that-changed-political-contours-of-india-1568051-2019-07-13}}</ref>\n\n== Usage in violent incidents ==\nIn 1992, during riots and [[Demolition of Babri Masjid]], the same slogans were raised.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/cover-story/story/19921231-babri-masjid-demolition-when-men-in-saffron-bandanas-struck-screaming-the-name-of-ram-767472-2013-05-21|title=Babri Masjid demolition: When men in saffron bandanas struck screaming the name of Ram|first1=Ravi Shankar|last1=May 21|first2=2013 ISSUE DATE:|last2=December 31|first3=1992UPDATED:|last3=July 25|first4=2013 13:22|last4=Ist|website=India Today}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=D'Costa |first1=Jasmine |title=Matter of Geography |date=2017 |publisher=Mosaic Press |isbn=978-1-77161-247-0 |url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=TLRJDwAAQBAJ&lpg=PT41&dq=Jai%20Shri%20Ram&pg=PT41#v=onepage&q=Jai%20Shri%20Ram&f=false |accessdate=11 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, before his [[Tabrez Ansari lynching|lynching, Tabrez Ansari]] was forced by the mob to chant religious slogans \"Jai Shree Ram\" and \"Jai Hanuman\".<ref name=\"BBC chant\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-48882053|title=The Hindu chant that became a murder cry|date=July 10, 2019|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\nOn February 2020, in an [[Gargi College molestations|incident of mass molestation]] and sexual harassment at [[Gargi College]], the [[Communist Party of India|CPI's]] women association alleged that the perpetrators were chanting the slogan of \"Jay Shree Ram\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freepressjournal.in/india/they-shouted-jai-shri-slogans-cpis-womens-association-on-thugs-involved-in-gargi-college-mass-molestation-case|title='They shouted Jai Shri Slogans': CPI's women's association on thugs involved in Gargi College 'mass molestation' case|website=Free Press Journal}}</ref>\n\nThe chant was heard again later the same month as Hindutva-inspired rioters torched Muslim properties and houses during the [[North East Delhi riots]].<ref name=\"Delhi Riots\">{{cite news |title=Delhi Riots: Mosque Set on Fire in Ashok Nagar, Hanuman Flag Placed on Minaret |url=https://thewire.in/communalism/delhi-violence-mosque-set-on-fire-in-ashok-vihar-hanuman-flag-placed-on-top |accessdate=26 February 2020 |work=The Wire |date=25 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ground Report: In Riot City, Hindutva Mobs Rage With Impunity as Police Watch in Silence|url=https://thewire.in/communalism/delhi-riots-jai-shri-ram-hindutva-bjp|date=25 February 2020|accessdate=26 February 2020|website=The Wire}}</ref> At least 20 people were killed in over three days of riots. Wounded residents fleeing the area described being beaten by mobs chanting the slogan, and being stopped multiple times by Hindus demanding they pull down their pants to show whether or not they were circumcised. <ref>{{cite news|title=Communal Violence Over India's Citizenship Law Leaves 20 Dead Amid Trump's Visit|url=https://time.com/5790831/india-hindu-muslim-clashes-trump-modi/|date=26 February 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|website=Time}}</ref> In one instance, an 85-year-old woman was burnt alive.<ref name=TIME/><ref>\nAarefa Johari, [https://scroll.in/article/954422/an-85-year-old-woman-was-burnt-to-death-in-her-home-in-delhis-gamri-extension An 85-year-old woman was burnt to death in her home in Delhi\u2019s Gamri extension], Scroll.in, 26 February 2020.\n</ref> The rioters were reported to have kept chanting \"Jai Shri Ram\" while beating their victims.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/02/25/world/asia/ap-as-trump-india-protests.html Death Toll Rises to 24 From Delhi Riots During Trump Trip], The New York Times, 25 February 2020.</ref> The police were also found to join in the chant while siding with the Hindu mobs.<ref>Kaushal Shroff, [https://caravanmagazine.in/conflict/delhi-violence-cops-shouted-jai-shri-ram-with-armed-hindu-mob-charged-at-muslims Delhi violence: Cops shouted \"Jai Shri Ram\" with armed Hindu mob, charged at Muslims], The Caravan, 25 February 2020.</ref> The Muslims were told ''Hindustan me rehna hoga, Jai Shri Ram kehna hoga'' (\"if you want to stay in India, you will have to chant Jai Shri Ram\").<ref>Kaushal Shroff, [https://caravanmagazine.in/conflict/delhi-violence-cops-shouted-jai-shri-ram-with-armed-hindu-mob-charged-at-muslims Delhi violence: Cops shouted \u201cJai Shri Ram\u201d with armed Hindu mob, charged at Muslims], The Caravan, 25 February 2020.</ref> Indian journalist [[Rana Ayyub]], writing in ''[[TIME]]'', commented that the slogan had become a \"racist [[Dog-whistle politics|dog whistle]]\" against Muslims.<ref name=TIME>\nRana Ayyub, [https://time.com/5791759/narendra-modi-india-delhi-riots-violence-muslim/ Narendra Modi Looks the Other Way as New Delhi Burns], ''TIME'', 28 February 2020.\n</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Vishva Hindu Parishad]]\n[[Category:Sangh Parivar]]\n[[Category:Ayodhya dispute]]\n[[Category:Violence against Muslims]]\n", "name_user": "2405:204:2295:b204::22ad:c0a0", "label": "unsafe"